[src:fine-grained-complexity/3sum] In computational complexity theory, the **3SUM** problem asks if a given set of n real numbers contains three elements that sum to zero.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/3sum] A generalized version, k -SUM, asks the same question on k elements, rather than simply 3.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/3sum] 3SUM can be easily solved in $O(n^{2})$ time, and matching $\Omega (n^{\lceil k/2\rceil })$ lower bounds are known in some specialized models of computation (Erickson 1999).
[src:fine-grained-complexity/3sum] It was conjectured that any deterministic algorithm for the 3SUM requires $\Omega (n^{2})$ time.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/3sum] In 2014, the original 3SUM conjecture was refuted by Allan Grønlund and Seth Pettie who gave a deterministic algorithm that solves 3SUM in $O(n^{2}/({\log n}/{\log \log n})^{2/3})$ time.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/3sum] Additionally, Grønlund and Pettie showed that the 4-linear decision tree complexity of 3SUM is $O(n^{3/2}{\sqrt {\log n}})$ .
[src:fine-grained-complexity/3sum] These bounds were subsequently improved.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/3sum] Kane, Lovett, and Moran showed that the 6-linear decision tree complexity of 3SUM is $O(n{\log ^{2}n})$ .
[src:fine-grained-complexity/3sum] The latter bound is tight (up to a logarithmic factor).
[src:fine-grained-complexity/3sum] It is still conjectured that 3SUM is unsolvable in $O(n^{2-\Omega (1)})$ expected time.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/3sum] When the elements are integers in the range $[-N,\dots ,N]$ , 3SUM can be solved in $O(n+N\log N)$ time by representing the input set S as a bit vector, computing the set $S+S$ of all pairwise sums as a discrete convolution using the fast Fourier transform, and finally comparing this set to S .
[src:fine-grained-complexity/3sum] Suppose the input array is $S[0..n-1]$ .
[src:fine-grained-complexity/3sum] In integer (word RAM) models of computing, 3SUM can be solved in $O(n^{2})$ time on average by inserting each number $S[i]$ into a hash table, and then, for each index i and j , checking whether the hash table contains the integer $-(S[i]+S[j])$ .
[src:fine-grained-complexity/3sum] It is also possible to solve the problem in the same time in a comparison-based model of computing or real RAM, for which hashing is not allowed.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/3sum] The algorithm below first sorts the input array and then tests all possible pairs in a careful order that avoids the slowdown of a binary search per pair, achieving worst-case $O(n^{2})$ time, as follows.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/3sum] The following example shows this algorithm's execution on a small sorted array.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/3sum] Current values of **a** are shown in red, values of **b** and **c** are shown in magenta.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/3sum] The correctness of the algorithm can be seen as follows.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/3sum] Suppose we have a solution a + b + c = 0.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/3sum] Since the pointers only move in one direction, we can run the algorithm until the leftmost pointer points to a.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/3sum] Run the algorithm until either one of the remaining pointers points to b or c, whichever occurs first.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/3sum] Then the algorithm will run until the last pointer points to the remaining term, giving the affirmative solution.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/3sum] Instead of looking for numbers whose sum is 0, it is possible to look for numbers whose sum is any constant *C*.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/3sum] The simplest way would be to modify the original algorithm to search the hash table for the integer ⁠ $(C-(S[i]+S[j]))$ ⁠.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/3sum] For example, if A=[1,2,3,4] and if you are asked to find 3SUM for *C*=4, then subtract 4/3 from all the elements of A, and solve it in the usual 3sum way, i.e., ⁠ $(a-C/3)+(b-C/3)+(c-C/3)=0$ ⁠.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/3sum] Instead of searching for the 3 numbers in a single array, we can search for them in 3 different arrays.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/3sum] Call the 1-array variant 3SUM×1 and the 3-array variant 3SUM×3.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/3sum] By the way we transformed the arrays, it is guaranteed that *a*∈*X*, *b*∈*Y*, *c*∈*Z*.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/3sum] Given a solver for 3SUM, the Conv3SUM problem can be solved in the following way.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/3sum] Given a solver for Conv3SUM, the 3SUM problem can be solved in the following way.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/3sum] Suppose that all elements are integers in the range: 0...*N*−1, and that the function *h* maps each element to an element in the smaller range of indices: 0...*n*−1.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/3sum] Initially, suppose that the mappings are unique (i.e. each cell in *T* accepts only a single element from *S*).
[src:fine-grained-complexity/3sum] This idealized solution doesn't work, because any hash function might map several distinct elements of *S* to the same cell of *T*.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/3sum] The trick is to create an array ⁠ $T^{*}$ ⁠ by selecting a single random element from each cell of *T*, and run Conv3SUM on ⁠ $T^{*}$ ⁠.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/3sum] If a solution is found, then it is a correct solution for 3SUM on *S*.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/3sum] If no solution is found, then create a different random ⁠ $T^{*}$ ⁠ and try again.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/3sum] Suppose there are at most *R* elements in each cell of *T*.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/3sum] Then the probability of finding a solution (if a solution exists) is the probability that the random selection will select the correct element from each cell, which is $(1/R)^{3}$ .
[src:fine-grained-complexity/3sum] By running Conv3SUM $R^{3}$ times, the solution will be found with a high probability.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/3sum] This requires to duplicate the elements of *S* when copying them into *T*, i.e., put every element $x\in S$ both in $T[h(x)]$ (as before) and in $T[h(x)]-1$ .
[src:fine-grained-complexity/3sum] So each cell will have 2*R* elements, and we will have to run Conv3SUM $(2R)^{3}$ times.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/3sum] A problem is called **3SUM-hard** if solving it in subquadratic time implies a subquadratic-time algorithm for 3SUM.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/3sum] The concept of 3SUM-hardness was introduced by Gajentaan & Overmars (1995).
[src:fine-grained-complexity/3sum] They proved that a large class of problems in computational geometry are 3SUM-hard, including the following ones.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/3sum] By now there are a multitude of other problems that fall into this category.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/3sum] An example is the decision version of X + Y sorting: given sets of numbers X and Y of n elements each, are there *n*² distinct *x* + *y* for *x* ∈ *X*, *y* ∈ *Y*?
[src:fine-grained-complexity/diameter-graph-theory] In graph theory, the **diameter** of a connected undirected graph is the farthest distance between any two of its vertices.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/diameter-graph-theory] That is, it is the diameter of a set for the set of vertices of the graph, and for the shortest-path distance in the graph.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/diameter-graph-theory] Diameter may be considered either for weighted or for unweighted graphs.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/diameter-graph-theory] Researchers have studied the problem of computing the diameter, both in arbitrary graphs and in special classes of graphs.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/diameter-graph-theory] The diameter of a disconnected graph may be defined to be infinite, or undefined.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/diameter-graph-theory] The degree diameter problem seeks tight relations between the diameter, number of vertices, and degree of a graph.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/diameter-graph-theory] One way of formulating it is to ask for the largest graph with given bounds on its degree and diameter.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/diameter-graph-theory] For any fixed degree, this maximum size is exponential in diameter, with the base of the exponent depending on the degree.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/diameter-graph-theory] The girth of a graph, the length of its shortest cycle, can be at most $2k+1$ for a graph of diameter k .
[src:fine-grained-complexity/diameter-graph-theory] The regular graphs for which the girth is exactly $2k+1$ are the Moore graphs.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/diameter-graph-theory] Only finitely many Moore graphs exist, but their exact number is unknown.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/diameter-graph-theory] They provide the solutions to the degree diameter problem for their degree and diameter.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/diameter-graph-theory] Small-world networks are a class of graphs with low diameter, modeling the real-world phenomenon of six degrees of separation in social networks.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/diameter-graph-theory] The diameter of a graph can be computed by using a shortest path algorithm to compute shortest paths between all pairs of vertices, and then taking the maximum of the distances that it computes.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/diameter-graph-theory] For instance, in a graph with positive edge weights, this can be done by repeatedly using Dijkstra's algorithm, once for each possible starting vertex.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/diameter-graph-theory] In a graph with n vertices and m edges, this takes time $O(mn+n^{2}\log n)$ .
[src:fine-grained-complexity/diameter-graph-theory] Computing all-pairs shortest paths is the fastest known method for computing the diameter of a weighted graph exactly.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/diameter-graph-theory] In an unweighted graph, Dijkstra's algorithm may be replaced by a breadth-first search, giving time $O(mn)$ .
[src:fine-grained-complexity/diameter-graph-theory] Alternatively, the diameter may be computed using an algorithm based on fast matrix multiplication, in time proportional to the time for multiplying $n\times n$ matrices, approximately $O(n^{2.37})$ using known matrix multiplication algorithms.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/diameter-graph-theory] For sparse graphs, with few edges, repeated breadth-first search is faster than matrix multiplication.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/diameter-graph-theory] Assuming the strong exponential time hypothesis, repeated breadth-first search is near-optimal: this hypothesis implies that no algorithm can achieve time $O(m^{2-\varepsilon })$ for any $\varepsilon >0$ .
[src:fine-grained-complexity/diameter-graph-theory] It is possible to approximate the diameter of a weighted graph to within an approximation ratio of 3/2, in time ${\tilde {O}}(\min(m^{3/2},mn^{2/3})$ , where the ${\tilde {O}}$ notation hides logarithmic factors in the time bound.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/diameter-graph-theory] Under the strong exponential time hypothesis, no substantially more accurate approximation, substantially faster than all pairs shortest paths, is possible.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/diameter-graph-theory] The diameter can be computed in linear time for interval graphs, and in near-linear time for graphs of bounded treewidth.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/diameter-graph-theory] In median graphs, the diameter can be found in the subquadratic time bound ${\tilde {O}}(n^{1.6456})$ .
[src:fine-grained-complexity/diameter-graph-theory] In any class of graphs closed under graph minors, such as the planar graphs, it is possible to compute the diameter in subquadratic time, with an exponent depending on the graph family.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/exponential-time-hypothesis] In computational complexity theory, the **exponential time hypothesis** or **ETH** is an unproven computational hardness assumption that was formulated by Impagliazzo & Paturi (1999).
[src:fine-grained-complexity/exponential-time-hypothesis] It states that satisfiability of 3-CNF Boolean formulas (3-SAT) cannot be solved in subexponential time, $2^{o(n)}$ .
[src:fine-grained-complexity/exponential-time-hypothesis] More precisely, the usual form of the hypothesis asserts the existence of a number $s_{3}>0$ such that all algorithms that correctly solve 3-SAT require time at least $2^{s_{3}n}.$ The exponential time hypothesis, if true, would imply that P ≠ NP, but it is a stronger statement.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/exponential-time-hypothesis] Beyond NP-complete problems, it implies that many known algorithms (including those with lower than exponential time) have optimal or near-optimal time complexity.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/exponential-time-hypothesis] The k -SAT problem is a version of the Boolean satisfiability problem in which the input to the problem is a Boolean expression in conjunctive normal form (that is, an *and* of *ors* of variables and their negations) with at most k variables per clause.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/exponential-time-hypothesis] The goal is to determine whether this expression can be made to be true by some assignment of Boolean values to its variables.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/exponential-time-hypothesis] 2-SAT has a linear time algorithm, but all known algorithms for larger k take exponential time, with the base of the exponential function depending on k .
[src:fine-grained-complexity/exponential-time-hypothesis] For instance, the WalkSAT probabilistic algorithm can solve k -SAT in average time $\left(2-{\frac {2}{k}}\right)^{n}n^{O(1)},$ where n is the number of variables in the given k -SAT instance.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/exponential-time-hypothesis] For each integer $k\geq 3$ , define $s_{k}$ to be the smallest number such that k -SAT can be solved in time $2^{s_{k}n+o(n)}$ .
[src:fine-grained-complexity/exponential-time-hypothesis] This minimum might not exist, if a sequence of better and better algorithms have correspondingly smaller exponential growth in their time bounds; in that case, define $s_{k}$ to be the infimum of the real numbers $\delta$ for which k -SAT can be solved in time $O(2^{\delta n})$ .
[src:fine-grained-complexity/exponential-time-hypothesis] Some sources define the exponential time hypothesis to be the slightly weaker statement that 3-SAT cannot be solved in time $2^{o(n)}$ .
[src:fine-grained-complexity/exponential-time-hypothesis] If there existed an algorithm to solve 3-SAT in time $2^{o(n)}$ , then $s_{3}$ would equal zero.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/exponential-time-hypothesis] If this were to be the case, then $s_{3}$ would equal zero even though there would be no single algorithm running in time $2^{o(n)}$ .
[src:fine-grained-complexity/exponential-time-hypothesis] A related variant of the exponential time hypothesis is the **non-uniform exponential time hypothesis**, which posits that there is no family of algorithms (one for each length of the input, in the spirit of advice) that can solve 3-SAT in time $2^{o(n)}$ .
[src:fine-grained-complexity/exponential-time-hypothesis] Because the numbers $s_{3},s_{4},\dots$ form a monotonic sequence that is bounded above by one, they must converge to a limit $s_{\infty }=\lim _{k\to \infty }s_{k}.$ The **strong exponential time hypothesis** (SETH) is the conjecture that $s_{\infty }=1$ .
[src:fine-grained-complexity/exponential-time-hypothesis] It is not possible for $s_{k}$ to equal $s_{\infty }$ for any finite k : as Impagliazzo, Paturi & Zane (2001) showed, there exists a constant $\alpha$ such that $s_{k}\leq s_{\infty }(1-\alpha /k)$ .
[src:fine-grained-complexity/exponential-time-hypothesis] Therefore, if the exponential time hypothesis is true, there must be infinitely many values of k for which $s_{k}$ differs from $s_{k+1}$ .
[src:fine-grained-complexity/exponential-time-hypothesis] Therefore, if 3-SAT could be solved in subexponential time, one could use this reduction to solve k -SAT in subexponential time as well.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/exponential-time-hypothesis] Equivalently, if $s_{k}>0$ for any $k>0$ , then $s_{3}>0$ as well, and the exponential time hypothesis would be true.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/exponential-time-hypothesis] Therefore, if the strong exponential time hypothesis is true, then there would be no algorithm for general CNF satisfiability that is significantly faster than a brute-force search over all possible truth assignments.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/exponential-time-hypothesis] However, if the strong exponential time hypothesis fails, it would still be possible for $s_{\operatorname {CNF} }$ to equal one.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/exponential-time-hypothesis] The exponential time hypothesis implies that many other problems in the complexity class SNP do not have algorithms whose running time is faster than $c^{n}$ for some constant c .
[src:fine-grained-complexity/exponential-time-hypothesis] These problems include graph k-colorability, finding Hamiltonian cycles, maximum cliques, maximum independent sets, and vertex cover on n -vertex graphs.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/exponential-time-hypothesis] Conversely, if any of these problems has a subexponential algorithm, then the exponential time hypothesis could be shown to be false.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/exponential-time-hypothesis] If cliques or independent sets of logarithmic size could be found in polynomial time, the exponential time hypothesis would be false.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/exponential-time-hypothesis] Therefore, even though finding cliques or independent sets of such small size is unlikely to be NP-complete, the exponential time hypothesis implies that these problems are non-polynomial.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/exponential-time-hypothesis] More generally, the exponential time hypothesis implies that it is not possible to find cliques or independent sets of size k in time $n^{o(k)}$ .
[src:fine-grained-complexity/exponential-time-hypothesis] The exponential time hypothesis also implies that it is not possible to solve the k-SUM problem (given n real numbers, find k of them that add to zero) in time $n^{o(k)}$ .
[src:fine-grained-complexity/exponential-time-hypothesis] The strong exponential time hypothesis implies that it is not possible to find k -vertex dominating sets more quickly than in time $n^{k-o(1)}$ .
[src:fine-grained-complexity/exponential-time-hypothesis] The exponential time hypothesis implies also that the weighted feedback arc set problem on tournaments does not have a parametrized algorithm with running time ${\textstyle O(2^{o({\sqrt {\operatorname {OPT} }})}n^{O(1)})}$ .
[src:fine-grained-complexity/exponential-time-hypothesis] It does however have a parameterized algorithm with running time ${\textstyle O(2^{O({\sqrt {\operatorname {OPT} }})}n^{O(1)})}$ .
[src:fine-grained-complexity/exponential-time-hypothesis] The strong exponential time hypothesis leads to tight bounds on the parameterized complexity of several graph problems on graphs of bounded treewidth.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/exponential-time-hypothesis] Equivalently, any improvement on these running times would falsify the strong exponential time hypothesis.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/exponential-time-hypothesis] The exponential time hypothesis also implies that any fixed-parameter tractable algorithm for edge clique cover must have double exponential dependence on the parameter.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/exponential-time-hypothesis] In the three-party set disjointness problem in communication complexity, three subsets of the integers in some range $[1,m]$ are specified, and three communicating parties each know two of the three subsets.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/exponential-time-hypothesis] The goal is for the parties to transmit as few bits to each other on a shared communications channel in order for one of the parties to be able to determine whether the intersection of the three sets is empty or nonempty.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/exponential-time-hypothesis] A trivial m -bit communications protocol would be for one of the three parties to transmit a bitvector describing the intersection of the two sets known to that party, after which either of the two remaining parties can determine the emptiness of the intersection.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/exponential-time-hypothesis] However, if there exists a protocol that solves the problem with $o(m)$ communication and $2^{o(m)}$ computation, it could be transformed into an algorithm for solving k -SAT in time $O(1.74^{n})$ for any fixed constant k , violating the strong exponential time hypothesis.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/exponential-time-hypothesis] Therefore, the strong exponential time hypothesis implies either that the trivial protocol for three-party set disjointness is optimal, or that any better protocol requires an exponential amount of computation.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/exponential-time-hypothesis] If the exponential time hypothesis is true, then 3-SAT would not have a polynomial time algorithm, and therefore it would follow that P ≠ NP.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/exponential-time-hypothesis] More strongly, in this case, 3-SAT could not even have a quasi-polynomial time algorithm, so NP could not be a subset of QP.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/exponential-time-hypothesis] However, if the exponential time hypothesis fails, it would have no implication for the P versus NP problem.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/exponential-time-hypothesis] In parameterized complexity theory, because the exponential time hypothesis implies that there does not exist a fixed-parameter-tractable algorithm for maximum clique, it also implies that W[1] ≠ FPT.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/exponential-time-hypothesis] It is an important open problem in this area whether this implication can be reversed: does W[1] ≠ FPT imply the exponential time hypothesis?
[src:fine-grained-complexity/exponential-time-hypothesis] The exponential time hypothesis is equivalent to the statement that M[1] ≠ FPT, and the question of whether ${\mathsf {M}}[i]\subseteq {\mathsf {W}}[i]$ for $i>1$ is also open.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/exponential-time-hypothesis] It is also possible to prove implications in the other direction, from the failure of a variation of the strong exponential time hypothesis to separations of complexity classes.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/exponential-time-hypothesis] As Williams (2010) shows, if there exists an algorithm A that solves Boolean circuit satisfiability in time $2^{n}/f(n)$ for some superpolynomially growing function f , then NEXPTIME is not a subset of P/poly.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/exponential-time-hypothesis] Williams shows that, if algorithm A exists, and a family of circuits simulating NEXPTIME in P/poly also existed, then algorithm A could be composed with the circuits to simulate NEXPTIME problems nondeterministically in a smaller amount of time, violating the time hierarchy theorem.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/exponential-time-hypothesis] Therefore, the existence of algorithm A proves the nonexistence of the family of circuits and the separation of these two complexity classes.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/fine-grained-reduction] In computational complexity theory, a **fine-grained reduction** is a transformation from one computational problem to another, used to relate the difficulty of improving the time bounds for the two problems.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/fine-grained-reduction] Intuitively, it provides a method for solving one problem efficiently by using the solution to the other problem as a subroutine.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/fine-grained-reduction] If problem A can be solved in time $a(n)$ and problem B can be solved in time $b(n)$ , then the existence of an $(a,b)$ -reduction from problem A to problem B implies that any significant speedup for problem B would also lead to a speedup for problem A .
[src:fine-grained-complexity/fine-grained-reduction] Let A and B be computational problems, specified as the desired output for each possible input.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/fine-grained-reduction] Let a and b both be time-constructible functions that take an integer argument n and produce an integer result.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/fine-grained-reduction] Usually, a and b are the time bounds for known or naive algorithms for the two problems, and often they are monomials such as $n^{2}$ .
[src:fine-grained-complexity/fine-grained-reduction] An $(a,b)$ -reduction is given by the mapping from $\epsilon$ to the pair of an algorithm and $\delta$ .
[src:fine-grained-complexity/fine-grained-reduction] Suppose A is $(a,b)$ -reducible to B , and there exists $\epsilon >0$ such that B can be solved in time $O{\bigl (}b(n)^{1-\epsilon }{\bigr )}$ .
[src:fine-grained-complexity/fine-grained-reduction] Then, with these assumptions, there also exists $\delta >0$ such that A can be solved in time $O{\bigl (}a(n)^{1-\delta }{\bigr )}$ .
[src:fine-grained-complexity/fine-grained-reduction] Namely, let $\delta$ be the value given by the $(a,b)$ -reduction, and solve A by applying the transformation of the reduction and using the fast algorithm for B for each resulting subproblem.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/fine-grained-reduction] Equivalently, if A cannot be solved in time significantly faster than $a(n)$ , then B cannot be solved in time significantly faster than $b(n)$ .
[src:fine-grained-complexity/fine-grained-reduction] Fine-grained reductions were defined, in the special case that a and b are equal monomials, by Virginia Vassilevska Williams and Ryan Williams in 2010.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/fine-grained-reduction] According to their results, either all of these problems have time bounds with exponents less than three, or none of them do.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/fine-grained-reduction] The term "fine-grained reduction" comes from later work by Virginia Vassilevska Williams in an invited presentation at the 10th International Symposium on Parameterized and Exact Computation.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/fine-grained-reduction] Although the original definition of fine-grained reductions involved deterministic algorithms, the corresponding concepts for randomized algorithms and nondeterministic algorithms have also been considered.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/np-hardness] In computational complexity theory, a computational problem *H* is called **NP-hard** if, for every problem *L* which can be solved in non-deterministic polynomial-time, there is a polynomial-time reduction from *L* to *H*.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/np-hardness] That is, assuming a solution for *H* takes 1 unit time, *H*'s solution can be used to solve *L* in polynomial time.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/np-hardness] As a consequence, finding a polynomial time algorithm to solve a single NP-hard problem would give polynomial time algorithms for all the problems in the complexity class NP.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/np-hardness] As it is suspected, but unproven, that P≠NP, it is unlikely that any polynomial-time algorithms for NP-hard problems exist.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/np-hardness] A simple example of an NP-hard problem is the subset sum problem.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/np-hardness] Informally, if *H* is NP-hard, then it is at least as difficult to solve as the problems in NP.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/np-hardness] However, the opposite direction is not true: some problems are undecidable, and therefore even more difficult to solve than all problems in NP, but they are probably not NP-hard (unless P=NP).
[src:fine-grained-complexity/np-hardness] A decision problem *H* is NP-hard when for every problem *L* in NP, there is a polynomial-time many-one reduction from *L* to *H*.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/np-hardness] Another definition is to require that there be a polynomial-time reduction from an NP-complete problem *G* to *H*.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/np-hardness] As any problem *L* in NP reduces in polynomial time to *G*, *L* reduces in turn to *H* in polynomial time so this new definition implies the previous one.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/np-hardness] It does not restrict the class NP-hard to decision problems, and it also includes search problems or optimization problems.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/np-hardness] If P ≠ NP, then NP-hard problems could not be solved in polynomial time.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/np-hardness] Some NP-hard optimization problems can be polynomial-time approximated up to some constant approximation ratio (in particular, those in APX) or even up to any approximation ratio (those in PTAS or FPTAS).
[src:fine-grained-complexity/np-hardness] There are many classes of approximability, each one enabling approximation up to a different level.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/np-hardness] All NP-complete problems are also NP-hard (see List of NP-complete problems).
[src:fine-grained-complexity/np-hardness] For example, the optimization problem of finding the least-cost cyclic route through all nodes of a weighted graph—commonly known as the travelling salesman problem—is NP-hard.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/np-hardness] The subset sum problem is another example: given a set of integers, does any non-empty subset of them add up to zero?
[src:fine-grained-complexity/np-hardness] That is a decision problem and happens to be NP-complete.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/np-hardness] There are decision problems that are *NP-hard* but not *NP-complete* such as the halting problem.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/np-hardness] That is the problem which asks "given a program and its input, will it run forever?" That is a *yes*/*no* question and so is a decision problem.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/np-hardness] It is easy to prove that the halting problem is NP-hard but not NP-complete.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/np-hardness] For example, the Boolean satisfiability problem can be reduced to the halting problem by transforming it to the description of a Turing machine that tries all truth value assignments and when it finds one that satisfies the formula it halts and otherwise it goes into an infinite loop.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/np-hardness] It is also easy to see that the halting problem is not in *NP* since all problems in NP are decidable in a finite number of operations, but the halting problem, in general, is undecidable.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/np-hardness] There are also NP-hard problems that are neither *NP-complete* nor *Undecidable*.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/np-hardness] For instance, the language of true quantified Boolean formulas is decidable in polynomial space, but not in non-deterministic polynomial time (unless NP = PSPACE).
[src:fine-grained-complexity/np-hardness] NP-hard problems do not have to be elements of the complexity class NP.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/np-hardness] Class of problems which are at least as hard as the hardest problems in NP.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/np-hardness] Problems that are NP-hard do not have to be elements of NP; indeed, they may not even be decidable.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/np-hardness] Class of decision problems which contains the hardest problems in NP.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/np-hardness] Each NP-complete problem has to be in NP.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/np-hardness] At most as hard as NP, but not necessarily in NP.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/np-hardness] Decision problems that are both NP-hard and NP-easy, but not necessarily in NP.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/np-hardness] If P and NP are different, then there exist decision problems in the region of NP that fall between P and the NP-complete problems.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/reduction-complexity] In computability theory and computational complexity theory, a **reduction** is an algorithm for transforming one problem into another problem.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/reduction-complexity] A sufficiently efficient reduction from one problem to another may be used to show that the second problem is at least as difficult as the first.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/reduction-complexity] Intuitively, problem *A* is **reducible** to problem *B*, if an algorithm for solving problem *B* efficiently (if it exists) could also be used as a subroutine to solve problem *A* efficiently.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/reduction-complexity] When this is true, solving *A* cannot be harder than solving *B*.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/reduction-complexity] "Harder" means having a higher estimate of the required computational resources in a given context (e.g., higher time complexity, greater memory requirement, need for extra hardware processor cores for a parallel solution compared to a single-threaded solution, etc.).
[src:fine-grained-complexity/reduction-complexity] The existence of a reduction from *A* to *B* can be written in the shorthand notation *A* ≤m *B*, usually with a subscript on the ≤ to indicate the type of reduction being used (m : many-one reduction, p : polynomial reduction).
[src:fine-grained-complexity/reduction-complexity] The mathematical structure generated on a set of problems by the reductions of a particular type generally forms a preorder, whose equivalence classes may be used to define degrees of unsolvability and complexity classes.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/reduction-complexity] A very simple example of a reduction is from *multiplication* to *squaring*.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/reduction-complexity] Suppose all we know how to do is to add, subtract, take squares, and divide by two.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/reduction-complexity] We also have a reduction in the other direction; obviously, if we can multiply two numbers, we can square a number.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/reduction-complexity] This seems to imply that these two problems are equally hard.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/reduction-complexity] This kind of reduction corresponds to Turing reduction.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/reduction-complexity] However, the reduction becomes much harder if we add the restriction that we can only use the squaring function one time, and only at the end.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/reduction-complexity] Going in the other direction, however, we can certainly square a number with just one multiplication, only at the end.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/reduction-complexity] Using this limited form of reduction, we have shown the unsurprising result that multiplication is harder in general than squaring.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/reduction-complexity] Reducibility is a preordering, that is, a reflexive and transitive relation, on **P**(**N**)×**P**(**N**), where **P**(**N**) is the power set of the natural numbers.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/reduction-complexity] As described in the example above, there are two main types of reductions used in computational complexity theory, the many-one reduction and the Turing reduction.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/reduction-complexity] Many-one reductions map *instances* of one problem to *instances* of another; Turing reductions *compute* the solution to one problem, assuming the other problem is easy to solve.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/reduction-complexity] The many-one reduction is a stronger type of Turing reduction, and is more effective at separating problems into distinct complexity classes.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/reduction-complexity] However, the increased restrictions on many-one reductions make them more difficult to find.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/reduction-complexity] A problem is complete for a complexity class if every problem in the class reduces to that problem, and it is also in the class itself.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/reduction-complexity] In this sense the problem represents the class, since any solution to it can, in combination with the reductions, be used to solve every problem in the class.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/reduction-complexity] However, in order to be useful, reductions must be *easy*.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/reduction-complexity] However, this does not achieve much, because even though we can solve the new problem, performing the reduction is just as hard as solving the old problem.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/reduction-complexity] Likewise, a reduction computing a noncomputable function can reduce an undecidable problem to a decidable one.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/reduction-complexity] Therefore, the appropriate notion of reduction depends on the complexity class being studied.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/reduction-complexity] When studying the complexity class NP and many harder classes such as the polynomial hierarchy, polynomial-time reductions are used.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/reduction-complexity] When studying classes within P such as NC and NL, log-space reductions are used.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/reduction-complexity] Reductions are also used in computability theory to show whether problems are or are not solvable by machines at all; in this case, reductions are restricted only to computable functions (for many-one reductions) or oracle machines (for Turing reductions).
[src:fine-grained-complexity/reduction-complexity] In the case of optimization (maximization or minimization) problems, we often think in terms of approximation-preserving reductions.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/reduction-complexity] Suppose we have two optimization problems such that instances of one problem can be mapped onto instances of the other, in a way that nearly optimal solutions to instances of the latter problem can be transformed back to yield nearly optimal solutions to the former.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/reduction-complexity] The following example shows how to use reduction from the halting problem to prove that a language is undecidable.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/reduction-complexity] Suppose *H*(*M*, *w*) is the problem of determining whether a given Turing machine *M* halts (by accepting or rejecting) on input string *w*.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/reduction-complexity] This language is known to be undecidable.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/reduction-complexity] Suppose *E*(*M*) is the problem of determining whether the language a given Turing machine *M* accepts is empty (in other words, whether *M* accepts any strings at all).
[src:fine-grained-complexity/reduction-complexity] We show that *E* is undecidable by a reduction from *H*.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/reduction-complexity] To obtain a contradiction, suppose *R* is a decider for *E*.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/reduction-complexity] We will use this to produce a decider *S* for *H* (which we know does not exist).
[src:fine-grained-complexity/reduction-complexity] Given input *M* and *w* (a Turing machine and some input string), define *S*(*M*, *w*) with the following behavior: *S* creates a Turing machine *N* that accepts only if the input string to *N* is *w* and *M* halts on input *w*, and does not halt otherwise.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/reduction-complexity] The decider *S* can now evaluate *R*(*N*) to check whether the language accepted by *N* is empty.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/reduction-complexity] If *R* accepts *N*, then the language accepted by *N* is empty, so in particular *M* does not halt on input *w*, so *S* can reject.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/reduction-complexity] If *R* rejects *N*, then the language accepted by *N* is nonempty, so *M* does halt on input *w*, so *S* can accept.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/reduction-complexity] Thus, if we had a decider *R* for *E*, we would be able to produce a decider *S* for the halting problem *H*(*M*, *w*) for any machine *M* and input *w*.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/reduction-complexity] Since we know that such an *S* cannot exist, it follows that the language *E* is also undecidable.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/time-hierarchy-theorem] In computational complexity theory, the **time hierarchy theorems** are important statements about time-bounded computation on Turing machines.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/time-hierarchy-theorem] Informally, these theorems say that given more time, a Turing machine can solve more problems.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/time-hierarchy-theorem] For example, there are problems that can be solved with *n*2 time but not *n* time, where *n* is the input length.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/time-hierarchy-theorem] The time hierarchy theorem for deterministic multi-tape Turing machines was first proven by Richard E.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/time-hierarchy-theorem] Stearns improved the efficiency of the universal Turing machine.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/time-hierarchy-theorem] Consequent to the theorem, for every deterministic time-bounded complexity class, there is a strictly larger time-bounded complexity class, and so the time-bounded hierarchy of complexity classes does not completely collapse.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/time-hierarchy-theorem] The left-hand class involves little o notation, referring to the set of decision problems solvable in asymptotically **less** than *f*(*n*) time.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/time-hierarchy-theorem] In particular, this shows that ${\mathsf {DTIME}}(n^{a})\subsetneq {\mathsf {DTIME}}(n^{b})$ if and only if $a<b$ , so we have an infinite time hierarchy.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/time-hierarchy-theorem] The time hierarchy theorem for nondeterministic Turing machines was originally proven by Stephen Cook in 1972.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/time-hierarchy-theorem] It was improved to its current form via a complex proof by Joel Seiferas, Michael Fischer, and Albert Meyer in 1978.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/time-hierarchy-theorem] Finally in 1983, Stanislav Žák achieved the same result with the simple proof taught today.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/time-hierarchy-theorem] The analogous theorems for space are the space hierarchy theorems.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/time-hierarchy-theorem] A similar theorem is not known for time-bounded probabilistic complexity classes, unless the class also has one bit of advice.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/time-hierarchy-theorem] Both theorems use the notion of a time-constructible function.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/time-hierarchy-theorem] A function $f:\mathbb {N} \rightarrow \mathbb {N}$ is time-constructible if there exists a deterministic Turing machine such that for every $n\in \mathbb {N}$ , if the machine is started with an input of *n* ones, it will halt after precisely *f*(*n*) steps.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/time-hierarchy-theorem] All polynomials with non-negative integer coefficients are time-constructible, as are exponential functions such as 2*n*.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/time-hierarchy-theorem] We need to prove that some time class **TIME**(*g*(*n*)) is strictly larger than some time class **TIME**(*f*(*n*)).
[src:fine-grained-complexity/time-hierarchy-theorem] We do this by constructing a machine which cannot be in **TIME**(*f*(*n*)), by diagonalization.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/time-hierarchy-theorem] We then show that the machine is in **TIME**(*g*(*n*)), using a simulator machine.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/time-hierarchy-theorem] We include here a proof of a weaker result, namely that **DTIME**(*f*(*n*)) is a strict subset of **DTIME**(*f*(2*n* + 1)3), as it is simpler but illustrates the proof idea.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/time-hierarchy-theorem] See the bottom of this section for information on how to extend the proof to *f*(*n*)log*f*(*n*).
[src:fine-grained-complexity/time-hierarchy-theorem] It is the set of pairs of machines and inputs to those machines (*M*,*x*) so that the machine *M* accepts within *f*(|*x*|) steps.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/time-hierarchy-theorem] Here, *M* is a deterministic Turing machine, and *x* is its input (the initial contents of its tape). [*M*] denotes an input that encodes the Turing machine *M*.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/time-hierarchy-theorem] Let *m* be the size of the tuple ([*M*], *x*).
[src:fine-grained-complexity/time-hierarchy-theorem] At each step, the simulating machine needs to look through the definition of *M* to decide what the next action would be.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/time-hierarchy-theorem] so that if we substitute 2*n* + 1 for *m*, we get the desired result.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/time-hierarchy-theorem] Let us assume that *Hf* is in this time complexity class, and we will reach a contradiction.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/time-hierarchy-theorem] We use this *K* to construct another machine, *N*, which takes a machine description [*M*] and runs *K* on the tuple ([*M*], [*M*]), ie.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/time-hierarchy-theorem] M is simulated on its own code by *K*, and then *N* accepts if *K* rejects, and rejects if *K* accepts.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/time-hierarchy-theorem] If *n* is the length of the input to *N*, then *m* (the length of the input to *K*) is twice *n* plus some delimiter symbol, so *m* = 2*n* + 1.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/time-hierarchy-theorem] If *g*(*n*) is a time-constructible function, and *f*(*n*+1) = o(*g*(*n*)), then there exists a decision problem which cannot be solved in non-deterministic time *f*(*n*) but can be solved in non-deterministic time *g*(*n*).
[src:fine-grained-complexity/time-hierarchy-theorem] In other words, the complexity class **NTIME**(*f*(*n*)) is a strict subset of **NTIME**(*g*(*n*)).
[src:fine-grained-complexity/time-hierarchy-theorem] The time hierarchy theorems guarantee that the deterministic and non-deterministic versions of the exponential hierarchy are genuine hierarchies: in other words **P** ⊊ **EXPTIME** ⊊ **2-EXP** ⊊ ... and **NP** ⊊ **NEXPTIME** ⊊ **2-NEXP** ⊊ ....
[src:fine-grained-complexity/time-hierarchy-theorem] The theorem also guarantees that there are problems in **P** requiring arbitrarily large exponents to solve; in other words, **P** does not collapse to **DTIME**(*n**k*) for any fixed *k*.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/time-hierarchy-theorem] For example, there are problems solvable in *n*5000 time but not *n*4999 time.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/time-hierarchy-theorem] This is one argument against Cobham's thesis, the convention that **P** is a practical class of algorithms.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/time-hierarchy-theorem] If such a collapse did occur, we could deduce that **P** ≠ **PSPACE**, since it is a well-known theorem that **DTIME**(*f*(*n*)) is strictly contained in **DSPACE**(*f*(*n*)).
[src:fine-grained-complexity/time-hierarchy-theorem] The gap of approximately $\log f(n)$ between the lower and upper time bound in the hierarchy theorem can be traced to the efficiency of the device used in the proof, namely a universal program that maintains a step-count.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/time-hierarchy-theorem] This can be done more efficiently on certain computational models.
[src:fine-grained-complexity/time-hierarchy-theorem] Thus, a constant-factor increase in the time bound allows for solving more problems, in contrast with the situation for Turing machines (see Linear speedup theorem).
